Sep 19 Mo\par
At JNU: This is exciting! It looks like if we had hand picked a place for service to the linguistic community, we could not have done better. Anvita is an active user with two more years on her project. She is on a SOAS grant for endangered languages. She is an expert on field linguistics, with long experience in doing it, and Toolbox is designed as a tool for that kind of linguist. She says data collection and descriptive presentation is growing in importance again in linguistics. South Asia is one of the most interesting and exciting places for fieldwork. Living in South Asia looks like the right kind of place for doing this kind of work. The Lord has obviously done a good thing here, and this looks like a big push toward the linguistic community support.\par
How much word would it take to get true structured XML on an export of interlinear? Some, but not a lot. It would have to work down each bundle, and collect the pieces. Presumably the collection of morpheme pieces would be nested under the word pieces. But the official annotation does not have space separated pieces under the words. It has whole chunks under the words, with matching hyphens to separate the pieces. That form would be a lot easier to output as XML. But it is a subset of the broader form, so it might be worth implementing the broader form if it isn't too complicated.\par
What I really need is direct contact with a knowledgable SOAS rep who can tell me what is the best layout and form. Anvita doesn't know that, and the information she has is not very clear on it. After I have that contact and information, then I can work on a package to do it as smoothly as possible, and I can have Anvita as a tester.\par
So for the moment I need to work on opening the SOAS contact(s) and getting the information about what would be most effective.\par
Sep 3 Sa\par
I need to calm down about progress and schedule.\par
I had a message from Steve White asking if Mac was coming end of this year, and it made me think about such things.\par
What happened to port?\par
I started in Nov last year. Then came Dec & Jan in US, which turned out less worktime than I had hoped. I started on wxWidgets sample app in NC in Jan, and spent Feb on it. Then came the note from Steve about Dan and the IME, which is the big thing that really blew away the port. I could not let them do a parallel version, not for something as far-reaching as IME support. It would have been almost impossible to fit it back together. In actuality, they never appeared to necessarily have the people to do the IME work, but the possibility was there. Anyway, I dove into IME in March & Apr, and made some good progress. But I also let myself do what added up to a month of consulting in Ktm, and then came the second US trip. At that point, TDF looked high priority, so it was done, even before further IME work, and that led to the plan of a release before the IME. There really are lots of things ready to go in this version. But because of the port being way past when I had hoped, and now  the IME also way past when I had hoped, I have a tendency to feel bad rather than good about Toolbox. The root problem is that both port and IME are not really my strong point, and I have had a hard time getting into them and making good progress, and it has been easy to let other things come in instead. But at the same time, I feel guilty as the proposed deadlines slide on and on.\par
How can I feel happier?\par
I have notified people of the new proposed deadlines, and no one is making major objections or insisting on bringing in people to help me. I suppose having others brought in is the biggest fear I have right now. I know from past experience that when number two comes in, they work rapidly without much worry about compatibility and consistency and not breaking things. They feel good because they do a lot of coding. I do less coding because I have to spend a lot of time explaining and working with them. And when they are done, I have to do a lot of follow-up coding to fix all the messes they have left. So, the end result is that whatever they are working on gets all the coding time, both from them and from me. I have found years ago already that I am better off just doing it myself. But that means I have to head off the efforts of others to come in and "help".\par
Thankfully, at the moment, no one is trying to come in and help, and no priority is pushing such that they would. The IME appears to be accepting the current schedule, plus that the temporary workaround is keeping some of them going for now. The port to Mac could draw a programmer, but that community doesn't seem to have enough resources to offer such. So, I think there is reasonable hope that I will be allowed to do it in my own way, and at my own speed. Karen may be going to help with the dialog boxes, and that might be good. On the other hand, she could help with documentation or other things, and that might be as good or better. On the other hand, she doesn't know as much about some things, so I will have to draft some anyway. Plus, she is not actually being very productive these days, beyond answering eml questions. She has a long way to go on TDF.\par
So, I need to thank the Lord for the current situation, and accept it, and use what wisdom I have to do my best. I have all of Sept and part of Oct to prepare a release. Other than the punc stuff I am doing right now, everything else is pretty optional whether it gets in this release or not. On the other hand, the list of things I hope for are really valuable things that will be great to have for users. So, what I need to do is prepare a reasonable release to put on LSB, and then keep working away, expecting more releases in the coming year.\par
Maybe one way to ask the question is: Am I feeling uncomfortable because I am doing the wrong thing in any way? Should I do something different? If I should do anything different, then I should figure that out, and change. If I should continue as is, then I should be happy about it, and I should work as quickly and effectively as I can.\par
I do feel a bit uncomfortable about my amount of work in a day and my rate of progress. I am making some good improvements by going to be earlier and expanding the morning. I also have been able to do some work in the afternoon recently, so maybe there is progress on that front.\par
I think the cold and the other leftover wearinesses from jet-lag and tiredness from all the travel have slowed me down and discouraged me. Also, as described above, the fact that so many things have come up in the past year has a tendency to leave me feeling insecure about the future. It is perfectly true that I don't know the future, and things could come up. On the other hand, last years things were pretty well anticipated in many ways, so it wasn't that they were sudden, drastic surprises. So, the best is to face the future with hope and confidence, trusting the Lord to handle the unexpected.\par
I have definitely been a bit depressed in various ways, and that is surely the worst of my problem at the moment. That is specifically what I am addressing this morning. Hopefully, recovery from the cold, time to recover from jet-lag and travel weariness, and time to get settled again will take care of most of the depression. Also, reducing the guilt from past missed deadlines will help. It will go as I convince myself that people understand that I had good reasons for delays, and so they are not upset at me about it. If I had done something bad, that would be one thing. But since it was external things, that is another thing.\par
So, rejoice in the Lord, be happy, enjoy the life God has provided, and work with energy and enthusiasm! Look forward to seeing Toolbox continue to do good things for people, and do my best to make them happen.\par
