I have been reading in the UTC library for 2 days, and I was reading a book about mental efficiency and concentration. It made me think about some of the problems I have in getting to work on Toolbox.\par
I think the worst is the overwhelming nature of the short deadline on the port. I need to tell myself that if the port takes longer, nothing bad will happen. In fact, the current delay on the port resulted in the Mac community buying me a new, fast, expensive Mac. So there won't necessarily be any bad results. I don't even need to say anything to the committee about it until sometime next year. My most recent message has now given me lots of leeway. If next summer or fall it is apparent that I won't make it by the end of the year, then I can talk to the committee about it again. But at the moment, I got no particular reactions from them to my message giving the reasons for delays so far.\par
The book on mental efficiency talked about reasons for distraction:\par
\tab 1. The way is unknown.\par
\tab 2. The way is blocked.\par
\tab 3. The way is boring or unpleasant.\par
\tab 4. The way offers no rest.\par
All of these have some truth for the port and IME, but especially three and four seem to apply.\par
I have been pushing away a variety of enhancements that could motivate me in favor of the port for over a year now, but the port has not moved much either. The result is that I feel discouraged, like I don't know how long it will actually take, and  like I don't know how long it might be before I can actually get back to more fun types of coding.\par
I think I probably need to open up to some of the little enhancements along the way and stop feeling that the port takes precedence over all the things I would like to do.\par
It is true that the port seems in some ways boring or unpleasant, but in fact, it won't be that bad most of the way. And if I do some other things along the way, then it won't be bad at all.\par
One thing I can do right now is to make test versions more personalized. Instead of thinking that a test version is for the whole tester list, I could announce it only to the subset who actually have a stake in it. Test versions for the whole tester list would be ones that are closer to release and that are supposed to be quite debugged, and that really need thorough testing. That way I can let the stakeholders of a particular new feature have it early, but it won't matter so much if there are a few known bugs outstanding in the test version they use.\par
On the other hand, I see quite a few stakeholders in the bugs I fixed since the last test version, so maybe a few more days is worth waiting. I will pray about it.\par
Lord, help me to have wisdom, and to have motivation on all of these things. You know that I like closure and would like to put out a test version and then be able to relax a little and do some clean-up. On the other hand, I hate to see Roland Fumey wait so long, so I want to get something to him very soon. I did notify him that I am working on it, so maybe another couple of days is all right.\par
Other good thoughts from the book on mental efficiency:\par
4 Factors in mental efficiency:\par
1. Intellectual: Attention, Reflection, Retention\par
2. Affective: Feelings, Emotions\par
3. Volitive: Motivation, Decision\par
4. Organic: Muscles, Blood, Respiration\par
Concentration is the main factor in efficiency and happiness.\par
Make haste slowly! Better because fewer repetitions.\par
Ideal = Emotion = Enthusiasm\par
Concentration = Efficiency = Joy\par
3 Stages in concentration\par
1. Adjustment: Preparation\par
2. Absorption\par
3. Saturation: Weakening\par
\tab 4. Fatigue comes if no break after weakening.\par
