\cf1 Written for Steve Feb 14, but not sent:\par
My suspicion is that the strongest reason for open source will come when we start to seriously support Linux. There are so many variations in Linux versions that it would take a lot of binaries to support them all. As a result, many programs are provided in source form so that anyone who wants to use them on an obscure version of Linux can compile to make their own binary. Probably many of these "open source" programs are never modified by users at all. But the ability to compile from the source gives a real benefit to some users. \par
This raises a real issue that I would like to discuss further with you before you go to the meetings. I wonder if it might be possible to get permission for SAG to make Toolbox open source in our own way and time, without pressure to do so before we are ready? I realize that raising the issue seriously at all could open a can of worms. But maybe you can test the waters and see if it might be possible to let out just a few worms. If so, maybe they can be put on hooks and dropped in the water to good effect.\par
The point of letting such worms out would be that in general, the Linux source will grow in parallel with the Mac source. When I have a usable subset of Toolbox available for Mac and Linux, then it might be useful to have the option of letting the source out to some Linux users, at least in some limited way. If the port were to go really well, there is a chance I might get to that point before next year's CTAG. \par
One option is to keep the worms in the can for now, and only start to let them out when the time comes that we can put them to use. If we let them out now, they may crawl away, or die before we need them. So I will trust your judgment on whether to broach the subject (the can) at this time or not. \par
Of course, I realize that Dan's motion and the follow-up from it last year may have already opened the can a little bit. But my impression is that it was sort of opened on the wrong end. Maybe I misunderstood, but I though the result was that we were told by Ac Affairs that they could force us to give the source to someone if they so chose, but that we were not authorized to give it out to anyeone else without their permission, and such permission would be considered on a case by case basis. If that is the current status, maybe it would improve if they were to give us an open permission. But I will also be very happy to leave status quo if that is better.\par
